<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-precalc-trig" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Trig</title>


  <p>
    Trigonometric functions are fundamental tools in calculus.
    They arise in problems involving motion, waves, oscillations, and periodic behavior,
    and they play a key role in limits, derivatives, and integrals.
    In this section, we review the core definitions and properties of trigonometric functions
    that will be used throughout the course.
  </p>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-trig-triangle">
    <title>Right Triangle Definitions</title>

    <p>
      We begin by defining sine and cosine using right triangles.
      These definitions apply when the angle is acute.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-trig-triangle">
      <title>Sine and Cosine (Right Triangle)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Given a right triangle and an acute angle <m>\theta</m>,
        </p>
        <me>
          \sin(\theta) = \dfrac{\text{opposite}}{\text{hypotenuse}},
          \qquad
          \cos(\theta) = \dfrac{\text{adjacent}}{\text{hypotenuse}}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In a right triangle, the side opposite <m>\theta</m> has length 3,
          the adjacent side has length 4, and the hypotenuse has length 5.
          Find <m>\sin(\theta)</m> and <m>\cos(\theta)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <me>
          \sin(\theta) = \dfrac{3}{5},
          \qquad
          \cos(\theta) = \dfrac{4}{5}.
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <remark>
      <p>
        While these definitions are intuitive, they apply only to acute angles.
        To extend trigonometric functions to all real numbers,
        we use the unit circle.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-trig-unit-circle">
    <title>The Unit Circle Definition</title>

    <p>
      The unit circle allows us to define trigonometric functions
      for any real number and is the framework used in calculus.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-unit-circle">
      <title>Sine and Cosine (Unit Circle)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the unit circle centered at the origin.
          For a real number <m>t</m>, let the point on the unit circle
          corresponding to angle <m>t</m> (measured in radians)
          have coordinates <m>(x,y)</m>.
          Then
        </p>
        <me>
          \cos(t) = x,
          \qquad
          \sin(t) = y.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <remark>
      <p>
        In calculus, angles are always measured in radians.
        This choice ensures that derivatives and limits involving
        trigonometric functions behave correctly.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Evaluate <m>\sin(\pi/2)</m> and <m>\cos(\pi)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <me>
          \sin(\pi/2) = 1,
          \qquad
          \cos(\pi) = -1.
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-trig-range">
    <title>Range and Boundedness</title>

    <p>
      One of the most important properties of sine and cosine
      in calculus is that their values are bounded.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-sin-cos-range">
      <title>Range of Sine and Cosine</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For all real numbers <m>x</m>,
        </p>
        <me>
          -1 \le \sin(x) \le 1,
          \qquad
          -1 \le \cos(x) \le 1.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <remark>
      <p>
        These inequalities follow directly from the unit circle:
        the <m>y</m>- and <m>x</m>-coordinates of points on the unit circle
        cannot exceed 1 in magnitude.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <p>
      This boundedness property is used frequently in calculus,
      especially when applying the Squeeze Theorem to evaluate limits.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-trig-misconceptions">
    <title>Important Algebraic Warnings</title>

    <p>
      Trigonometric functions do <em>not</em> behave like algebraic variables.
      In particular, common distributive or additive properties
      do not hold.
    </p>

    <remark xml:id="rmk-trig-not-distributive">
      <p>
        The following identities are <em>false</em> in general:
      </p>
      <me>
        \sin(AB) \neq \sin(A)\sin(B),
        \qquad
        \sin(A+B) \neq \sin(A) + \sin(B).
      </me>
      <p>
        Similar statements are false for cosine.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <p>
      These misconceptions are common sources of error,
      especially when simplifying expressions or computing limits.
      Trigonometric functions require their own identities,
      which we now preview.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-trig-identities-preview">
    <title>Angle Sum and Double Angle Formulas</title>

    <p>
      While sine and cosine do not distribute over addition,
      there are specific formulas that describe how they behave
      when angles are added or multiplied.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-angle-sum">
      <title>Angle Sum Formulas</title>
      <statement>
        <me>
          \begin{array}{rcl}
            \sin(A+B) &amp; = &amp; \sin(A)\cos(B) + \cos(A)\sin(B) \\
            \cos(A+B) &amp; = &amp; \cos(A)\cos(B) - \sin(A)\sin(B)
          \end{array}
        </me>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <remark>
      <p>
        From these formulas, we can derive double angle identities
        such as
        <m>\sin(2x) = 2\sin(x)\cos(x)</m>.
        These identities appear frequently in calculus problems,
        especially when working with integrals and limits.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <exercises xml:id="exercises-precalc-trig">
    <title>Practice Problems</title>

    <exercisegroup>
      <title>Concepts and Skills</title>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use a right triangle to find <m>\sin(\theta)</m> and <m>\cos(\theta)</m>
            if the adjacent side is 5 and the hypotenuse is 13.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Evaluate <m>\sin(\pi)</m>, <m>\cos(\pi/2)</m>, and <m>\cos(0)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain why <m>\sin(x)</m> is bounded but <m>x</m> is not.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            True or False: <m>\sin(2x) = 2\sin(x)</m>. Explain your reasoning.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>

      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use the range of cosine to explain why
            <m>\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 0} x\cos(1/x) = 0</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>
  </exercises>

</section>
